[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update [note: weekend reporting artifact extends to today's (10 Aug 2020) reports]:

- The Americas region reported 56.7% of the global newly reported cases and 62.9% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 10.5 million cases. The USA reported 37.5% of cases (53 893), followed by Brazil 34.8% (49 970), Colombia 6.7% (9674), Peru 5.0% (7137), Mexico 4.5% (6495), Argentina 4.3% (6134), and Chile 1.4% (2033).

- The European region reported 7.0% of the global newly reported cases and 4.5% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Russia reported 29.0% (5118) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by (Spain 0 % (0), Kazakhstan 10.7% (1883), France 0% (0), Turkey 6.7% (1182), Romania 6.5% (1145), the UK 6.0% (1062), Ukraine 5.7% (1008), Israel 4.3% (763), Poland 3.5% (624), Uzbekistan 3.5% (623), Netherlands 3.3% (577), Italy 2.6% (463), and Germany 2.5% (436). Countries not reporting any new cases include: Spain, France, and Sweden.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 3.7% of the global newly reported cases and 6.1% of global newly reported fatalities. Iraq reported 28.9% (2726) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran 21.4% (2020), Saudi Arabia 15.2% (1428), (Morocco 0% (0)), Pakistan 5.9% (557), Kuwait 5.5% (514), Bahrain 4.1% (382), Qatar 3.2% (297), Lebanon 3.1% (294), and Palestinian Authority 2.9% (277),. Cases are continuing to increase in Iraq. Morocco did not report any cases today (10 Aug 2020). This region remains highly active, with multiple countries still in a surge mode.

- The African region reported 4.2% of the global newly reported cases and 5.4% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 62.3% (6671) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Kenya 5.6% (599), Ethiopia 5.3% (565), Algeria 4.9% (521), Ghana 4.4% (470), and Nigeria 4.1% (437). While South Africa is the dominant country in the region, it has halved its daily case count in the past week.

- The Western Pacific region reported 2.0% of the global newly reported cases and 1.6% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 60.4% (3028) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 24.1% (1207), Australia 7.7% (386), Singapore 3.5% (175), China 2.4% (121), Viet Nam 0.58% (29), and South Korea 0.56% (28). Japan and Australia continue with elevated transmission.

- The South East Asia region reported 26.4% of the global newly reported cases and 19.4% of global deaths. India reported 92.7% (62 064) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 3.7% (2487), and Indonesia 2.8% (1893). India continues to be the driving force of the dominance of this region.

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same, even with weekend reporting artifact. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region, and the Western Pacific region representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions. While regional proportions may not reflect this, most of the regions have countries that have resurgences of cases associated with lifting of restrictions.

Figure 3. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 10 Aug 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the text above. - Mod.MPP]

