Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Note: there is weekend artifact in daily reported cases as some key surge countries in Latin America have not reported any cases today [10 Aug 2020]. Peru, Bolivia, Honduras, and Venezuela and there are still reduced reports from some states in Brazil and the USA.

Comparing today's numbers with yesterday's (9 Aug 2020), the global case count rose by 1.1% in the past 24 hours.

The USA, Brazil, and India are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts. In the past 24 hours, these 3 countries -- India (53 016), followed by USA (52 002), and Brazil (21 888) -- account for over half of all confirmed cases globally (52.2%). There were 4610 deaths reported in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, India is number one for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by USA, Brazil, Colombia, Spain, Argentina, Philippines, Mexico, Russia, and France. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 4854 to 53 016. Other hotspots are seen in the countries numbered 11-20 in this list: South Africa, Iraq, Bangladesh, Iran, Chile, Israel, Indonesia, Saudi Arabia, Germany, and Japan; their range of reported new cases is 1207 to 3739.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, there is virtually no change (a decrease of 0.12%,) and looking at daily reported deaths, the change is increased by 1.8%. The key question still remains as to whether transmission is in fact slowing down or whether this is a reporting artifact. Time will tell, but following the data reports showing major surges in countries that had been showing successes makes one wonder what is driving these reporting variances (I haven't changed my mind!).

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts and mortality, while the global 7-day averages seem to reflect a slowing down of reporting confirmed cases; albeit, I still wonder whether this is real or reflects a changing pattern with decreased testing. For example, the USA reported data suggests a slowing down of transmission over the past 2 weeks as seen by the comparative 7-day averages in reported new cases and deaths (see section [3E] above), but if one looks at the percentage of positive PCR tests, in the past 2 weeks the positivity rate is 9%, consistent with significant ongoing transmission that is not abating (see https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html). The most severely affected region is the Americas, with cases increasing daily, even though the comparative 7-day average suggests things may be slowing down (or reporting is slowing down). - Mod.MPP]
